# Ruby & Rails Standards

## Linting & Formatting

This project uses RuboCop for code style. Configuration is in `.rubocop.yml`.

**After making changes, run linting:**
```bash
bundle exec rubocop -a
```

This will auto-correct most style issues. Only fix remaining issues manually when there are actual linting failures.

## Method Visibility

Always mark internal methods as `private`:
```ruby
class MyService
  def public_method
    internal_helper
  end

  private

  def internal_helper
    # implementation
  end
end
```

## Dangerous Operations to AVOID

### Never use `update_all` or `delete_all`
These lock the entire table and block replication:
```ruby
# BAD - locks table
User.where(active: false).delete_all

# GOOD - row-by-row
User.where(active: false).find_each(&:destroy)
```

### Never wrap large updates in transactions
```ruby
# BAD - locks table for entire duration
ActiveRecord::Base.transaction do
  Branch.all.each { |b| b.update(cool: true) }
end

# GOOD - individual updates
Branch.find_each { |b| b.update(cool: true) }
```

## Query Best Practices

### Use `find_each` for large datasets
```ruby
# GOOD
User.where(active: true).find_each do |user|
  process(user)
end

# BAD - loads all into memory
User.where(active: true).each { |u| process(u) }
```

### Use `.select` to limit columns
```ruby
# GOOD - only loads needed columns
User.select(:id, :name).where(active: true)
```

### Let MySQL sort, not Ruby
```ruby
# GOOD - MySQL sorts
Territory.order(:abbr).pluck(:abbr)

# BAD - Ruby sorts (slower)
Territory.pluck(:abbr).sort
```

## Avoid Serialize Fields

Serialized fields hurt performance. Use proper table structure instead:
```ruby
# BAD
class User < ApplicationRecord
  serialize :preferences, JSON
end

# GOOD - use a separate table or JSON column type
```

## Audit Tracking

For models that need audit tracking:
```ruby
class MyModel < ApplicationRecord
  track_audit_data user: true
end
```

Requires `created_by` and `updated_by` columns in the table.
